root@kali-hash:/home/kali/thrukpolling# which python
/home/kali/thrukpolling/venv/bin/python

Perfect. That means your ExecStart will use:

/home/kali/thrukpolling/venv/bin/python

Now let's create the service properly.

1. Create the service file
sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/thrukcollector.service

Paste this:

[Unit]
Description=Huawei Thruk Traffic Collector
After=network.target

[Service]
Type=simple

User=root
Group=root

WorkingDirectory=/home/kali/thrukpolling

ExecStart=/home/kali/thrukpolling/venv/bin/python /home/kali/thrukpolling/thruk_collector.py

Restart=always
RestartSec=5

StandardOutput=journal
StandardError=journal

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

I used User=root because all of your commands and testing have been done as root. If you later want to run it as kali, we can change that.

2. Reload systemd
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
3. Enable it on boot
sudo systemctl enable thrukcollector

Expected output:

Created symlink /etc/systemd/system/multi-user.target.wants/thrukcollector.service → /etc/systemd/system/thrukcollector.service.
4. Start it
sudo systemctl start thrukcollector
5. Check its status
sudo systemctl status thrukcollector

You should see something like:

● thrukcollector.service
     Loaded: loaded
     Active: active (running)
6. Watch the live logs

This is much nicer than running the script manually:

journalctl -u thrukcollector -f

You should see output similar to:

Collecting data from Thruk...

GE0/0/22  UP
GE0/0/23  UP
GE0/0/24  DOWN

Saved 3 interfaces
RRDs updated
Graphs generated
7. Reboot test

After rebooting:

sudo reboot

Then check:

sudo systemctl status thrukcollector

If it shows:

Active: active (running)
